<br>
I myself earned an RSI injury over 7 years ago in my shoulder when I worked in a grocery store. I was one of those poor slobs who bagged your groceries. Only, they didn't train me how essential it was to lift bags with both hands, move from the waist and bend to put those bags in the cart. I lifted often with the left arm only. I noticed the pain and as you may know, muscle pain is gradual. You don't feel it hurt until the damage is already done, basically. It seemed to me that overnight, my shoulder was in so much pain, just the weight of my hand at the end of my wrist caused acute agony.<br>
<br>
My advice to anyone who does any kind of repetitive motions, like typing or lifting or pipeting or something that requires a lot of intense activity of small joints and whatever have you, to pay attention to what your body tells you. If you start to get numb, or achy -- please, stop what you're doing, take some ibuprofin which is GREAT for inflamations (or any other anti-inflamatory pain reliever). RSI can be a pain, it can ruin your career if it can't be cured, and it often requires lengthy recovery periods, and never -quite- goes away. (I still get aching twinges in my shoulder).<br>
<br>
RSI sucks. There are several books that you can read on them. We have one of them in the Stanford Business Library (unsurprisingly). And it is oft charged out by various people, and even has a waiting queue.<br>
<br>
Let me see if I can post an amazon.com link..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0965510999/qid=1064869057/sr=2-1/ref=sr_2_1/103-7326014-7111831">www.amazon.com/exec/obido...14-7111831</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
The name of the book is: It's not Carpal Tunnel Syndrome! RSI Theory and Therapy for computer professionals. <br>
<br>
It has a lot of good info about people who have been misdiagnosed, and often from people who got surgerys who should not have had them!!!<br>
<br>
There are some : Folks who bought this, bought this as well links, which lead you to other RSI injury types of books.<br>
<br>
This is such a misunderstood injury, and really should be researched by anyone who thinks they may have one, or does have one.<br>
<br>
